To solve IMO 2020 Problem 5, we identify the set of integers $n$ for which the condition implies all cards are equal. The condition is that for every pair of cards, their arithmetic mean is the geometric mean of some subset of cards.
We show that for any $n > 1$, the only decks satisfying the property are the constant decks.
Assume for contradiction a non-constant deck exists. Let $M$ be the maximum value. There must be some prime $p$ and some card $x$ such that $v_p(x) < v_p(M)$ (otherwise $M$ divides all cards, and being the maximum, all cards would equal $M$).
Let $k = \min_i v_p(\text{deck } i)$. Let $Z$ be the maximum value among all cards with $v_p(\text{card}) = k$.
Consider the pair $(Z, M)$. Their mean $A = (Z+M)/2$ equals the geometric mean of a subset $S$.
Since $Z < A < M$ (as $Z \le M$ and $v_p(Z) < v_p(M) \implies Z \neq M$), $S$ must contain some element $y > A > Z$.
By maximality of $Z$, any $y > Z$ has $v_p(y) > k$.
We derive a contradiction on the valuation $v_p$ of the equation $(Z+M)^N = 2^N \prod_{s \in S} s$.
For $p \neq 2$, $v_p(Z+M) = k$ while $v_p(2^N \prod s) \ge Nk + 1 > Nk$.
For $p = 2$, $v_p(Z+M) = k$ while $v_p(2^N \prod s) \ge N + Nk + 1 > Nk$.
Both cases yield a contradiction. Thus the deck is constant.

